Lorelei_lorpt-024_Philippines_Landslide_: :: snt1	  200 dead , 1,500 feared missing in Philippines landslide .
:: snt2	  TACLOBAN , Philippines , Feb 17 , 2006 .
:: snt3	  About 200 people were believed killed and 1,500 others were missing in the central Philippines on Friday when a landslide buried an entire village , the Red Cross said .
:: snt4	  Eyewitnesses said only a few houses were left standing after the landslide hit the village of Guinsaugon in the south of the Philippine island of Leyte .
:: snt5	  " There are about 1,500 missing , 200 dead , " Richard Gordon , the head of the Philippine Red Cross , said in a radio interview .
:: snt6	  The first footage from the devastated village showed a sea of mud covering what had been lush green valley farmland .
:: snt7	  Only a few sheets of tin roofing and the occasional coconut tree could be seen .
:: snt8	  Tiny groups of mud - spattered survivors were also shown , walking through the muck , apparently stunned by the scope of the destruction .
:: snt9	  In a televised address to the nation , President Gloria Arroyo said rescue teams were rushing to the area from " air , land and sea " to cope with the catastrophe .
:: snt10	  " I have ordered the Coast Guard and our entire naval force in the ( central Philippines ) region to the area , " she said .
:: snt11	  " Naval ships will be used as floating hospitals and command centres for relief and rescue . "
:: snt12	  Leyte Governor Rosette Lerias said the latest census indicated there were 375 houses with 3,000 people living in Guinsaugon before the landslide .
:: snt13	  She described the village as totally flattened .
:: snt14	  " It was like mud running down the mountain and it covered the village in seconds , " she said , quoting survivors .
:: snt15	  Experts blamed deforestation for the tragedy , which came after days of rainfall that was five times higher than usual .

:: snt16	  Lerias said that many Guinsaugon residents had been evacuated after landslides earlier in the week had killed more than 20 people on Leyte , but that many had returned Friday because the rains had stopped and the sun had come out.

:: snt17	  A mild 2.6 - magnitude earthquake which struck before the landslide may also have helped set off the wall of mud that crashed down on the village , said Rene Solidum , head of the government vulcanology office.
:: snt18	  " The area could have really been ready for a landslide because of the amount of rainfall and if there was a minor earthquake , it might have hastened it , " Solidum said .
:: snt19	  Army Colonel Nestor Sadirin , head of a rescue task force , said 16 dead bodies had been recovered so far and 100 people rescued .
:: snt20	  Leyte Congressman Roger Mercado said in a radio interview that the village had a population of 3,000 to 4,000 and expressed fears that as many as 2,000 people had been buried .

:: snt21	  Lerias called for more rescuers to come to the site to help look for bodies as heavy earth moving equipment could not work in the mud , which officials said was more than six metres (yards) deep in many areas.
:: snt22	  Volunteer rescue teams from the country's mining companies , skilled in digging through the earth to rescue people , were also going to the area , said President Arroyo said.
:: snt23	  Gordon said the Red Cross said was trying to dispatch sniffer dogs to hunt for survivors .
:: snt24	  Military helicopters were able to reach the area despite heavy clouds but the flights ceased after nightfall because the aircraft did not have night - flying capabilities.
:: snt25	  Lerias said a smaller landslide later in the afternoon caused no damage but left many of the rescuers worried about a possible new disaster .
:: snt26	  Relief groups called for drinking water , food , blankets and body bags to be brought to the scene .
:: snt27	  Provincial board member Eva Dumol said in a radio interview that heavy equipment that was already in the area to clear up earlier landslides was being sent to the Guinasaugon area .
:: snt28	  More than 5,000 people were killed in a combined flood and mudslide on Leyte in November 1991.
